press the Atlantic slave trade in more than thirty years, the book gathers experts in history, literature, historical geography, museum studies, and the history of medicine to analyse naval suppression in light of recent work on slavery and empire. Three sections reveal the policies, experiences and representations of slave-trade suppression from the perspectives of metropolitan Britons, liberated Africans, black sailors, colonialists, and naval officers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAntislavery movementszGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aSlave tradezAfricaxHistoryy19th century. 0aSlave tradezGreat BritainxHistory. 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aAfrican health.  aAtlantic slave trade.  aBritish Empire.  aBritish health.  aBritish policies.  aSierra Leone.  aWest Africa.  aanti-slave trade squadron.  ahistorical writing.  aliberated Africans.  anaval coercion.  apublic memory.  aslave-trade suppression.1 aBurroughs, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurroughs, Robert, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChristopher, Emma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuzzey, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuzzey, Richard, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLambert, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcAleer, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRankin, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWills, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 201